<subSubSection id="9E538C0D2A49DCB388DFA6121B95C975" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="A3E03C4BB0546F58CCEFF0A5034D4CA1" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4FBA387C8692665D84FE75184FA49A2C" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">
In the phylogenetic tree of 
<bibRefCitation id="7AA7F17A349A7F138C71F0F4B3797B05" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-015-0520-0" author="Heikkilae, M" journalOrPublisher="BioMed Central, Evolutionary Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" pagination="1 - 27" refId="B16" refString="Heikkilae, M, Mutanen, M, Wahlberg, N, Sihvonen, P, Kaila, L, 2015. Elusive ditrysian phylogeny: an account of combining systematized morphology with molecular data (Lepidoptera). BioMed Central, Evolutionary Biology 15 (260): 1 - 27, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-015-0520-0" title="Elusive ditrysian phylogeny: an account of combining systematized morphology with molecular data (Lepidoptera)." url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-015-0520-0" volume="15" year="2015">
<normalizedToken id="970C5BCE5FB0482D04E58F6C19305F4F" originalValue="Heikkilä">Heikkilae</normalizedToken>
et al. (2015)
</bibRefCitation>
, which was based on a combination of molecular and morphological data, the family emerged in the 
<taxonomicName id="9CE2AC940A236F204BA81AD2DABF054B" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1983" genus="Apoditrysia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" rank="genus">Apoditrysia</taxonomicName>
as sister group of 
<taxonomicName id="1C383020E728D3B71E219B94DD9E85D4" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1983" genus="Apoditrysia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Tortricoidea">Tortricoidea</taxonomicName>
. A similar result was recovered by the molecular study of 
<bibRefCitation id="1A31AB48538295499B858B36E767B3EE" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0058568" author="Regier, JC" journalOrPublisher="Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift Iris, Dresden" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" refId="B40" refString="Regier, JC, Mitter, C, Zwick, A, Cumming, MP, Kawahara, AY, Sohn, J-C, Zwickl, DJ, Cho, S, Davis, DR, Baixeras, J, Brown, J, Parr, C, Weller, S, Lees, DC, Mitter, KT, 2013. A large-scale, higher-level, molecular phylogenetic study of the insect order lepidoptera (moths and butterflies). PLoS ONE 8: e58568. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0058568" title="A large-scale, higher-level, molecular phylogenetic study of the insect order lepidoptera (moths and butterflies). PLoS ONE 8: e 58568." url="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0058568" year="2013">Regier et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
. This placement is in contrast to the morphological results of 
<bibRefCitation id="AD3E6F9B03DB467C1976B04D8A24137E" author="Friese, G" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" pagination="1 - 131" refId="B13" refString="Friese, G, 1960. Revision der palaearktischen Yponomeutidae unter besonderer Beruecksichtigung der Genitalien. Beitraege zur Entomologie 10 (1-2): 1 - 131" title="Revision der palaearktischen Yponomeutidae unter besonderer Beruecksichtigung der Genitalien." volume="10" year="1960">Friese (1960</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="9049CCAEAC3164B659B41314C54BC0C6" author="Friese, G" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" pagination="299 - 331" refId="B14" refString="Friese, G, 1962. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der ostpalaearktischen Yponomeutidae (Lepidoptera). Beitraege zur Entomologie 12 (3-4): 299 - 331" title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der ostpalaearktischen Yponomeutidae (Lepidoptera)." volume="12" year="1962">1962</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="65517C4044D89B22FA62737014C2EBC1" author="Friese, G" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" pagination="447 - 459" refId="B15" refString="Friese, G, 1966. Ergebnisse der Albanien Expedition 1961 des Deutschen Entomologischen Instituts. 52. Beitrag. Lepidoptera: Plutellidae. Beitraege zur Entomologie 16: 447 - 459" title="Ergebnisse der Albanien Expedition 1961 des Deutschen Entomologischen Instituts. 52. Beitrag. Lepidoptera: Plutellidae." volume="16" year="1966">1966</bibRefCitation>
), 
<bibRefCitation id="129124868370D483CA0BB956B419DF46" author="Moriuti, S" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Lepidopterological Society of Japan" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" pagination="52 - 59" refId="B35" refString="Moriuti, S, 1963. Remarks on the Paraprays anisocentra (Meyrick, 1922) (Plutellidae) with descriptions of larva and pupa. Transactions of the Lepidopterological Society of Japan 14 (3): 52 - 59" title="Remarks on the Paraprays anisocentra (Meyrick, 1922) (Plutellidae) with descriptions of larva and pupa." volume="14" year="1963">Moriuti (1963)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="BE201A29872ADBB438BF3C089A9A00BC" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/187631284X00064" author="Kyrki, J" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Scandinavica" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" pagination="71 - 84" refId="B23" refString="Kyrki, J, 1984. The Yponomeutoidea: a reassessment of the superfamily and its suprageneric groups (Lepidoptera). Entomologica Scandinavica 15: 71 - 84, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1163/187631284X00064" title="The Yponomeutoidea: a reassessment of the superfamily and its suprageneric groups (Lepidoptera)." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/187631284X00064" volume="15" year="1984">Kyrki (1984</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="80D47DB8AE85226C06F5C27358BD9ABE" author="Kyrki, J" journalOrPublisher="Nota lepidopterologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" pagination="28 - 42" refId="B24" refString="Kyrki, J, 1990. Tentative classification of holarctic Yponomeutoidea (Lepidoptera). Nota lepidopterologica 13 (1): 28 - 42" title="Tentative classification of holarctic Yponomeutoidea (Lepidoptera)." volume="13" year="1990">1990</bibRefCitation>
) who considered the group as belonging to the 
<taxonomicName id="AFAEDC1A6932EA298B05ED97CC6A2CCA" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1983" genus="Apoditrysia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Yponomeutoidea">Yponomeutoidea</taxonomicName>
. Alternative systematic positions in 
<taxonomicName id="620E5EB105F5CF11F49575A8594F0E5A" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1983" genus="Apoditrysia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Tineoidea">Tineoidea</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="DC5F5FF15210C09B5C3A2869C693B9AC" authorityName="Kyrki" authorityYear="1988" class="Insecta" family="Urodidae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Urodidae</taxonomicName>
were proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="9CD60C4ED9DF44CD08FCA6FF07E593F2" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1071/9780643101227" author="Common, IFB" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" refId="B11" refString="Common, IFB, 1990. Moths of Australia. Melbourne University Press, [VI +] 535 pp. https://doi.org/10.1071/9780643101227" title="Moths of Australia. Melbourne University Press, [VI +] 535 pp." url="https://doi.org/10.1071/9780643101227" year="1990">Common (1990)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="8C2A20E779EB54505B300E2662325C95" author="Heppner, JB" journalOrPublisher="Holarctic Lepidoptera 5, supplement 1" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" refId="B17" refString="Heppner, JB, 1998. Classification of Lepidoptera. Part 1. Introduction. Holarctic Lepidoptera 5, supplement 1" title="Classification of Lepidoptera. Part 1. Introduction." year="1998">Heppner (1998)</bibRefCitation>
respectively. In fact, there are a number of morphological traits which are shared by 
<taxonomicName id="86D6EA3E95D67FD0424E48A0DD0878D6" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Galacticidae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Galacticidae</taxonomicName>
and various groups in 
<taxonomicName id="D42A0D4FCA0EFF6D908D3F7339F98B61" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1983" genus="Apoditrysia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Tineoidea">Tineoidea</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F64379C2260C94A55AD2F2333E82534A" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1983" genus="Apoditrysia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Yponomeutoidea">Yponomeutoidea</taxonomicName>
. To these characters should be added the presence of an unscaled, transparent patch in the hindwings at the wing base lying between Cu1 and Cu2. This character went widely unnoticed and, occurring in most examined species of 
<taxonomicName id="9496E1A699B00C78DF184391824B07A6" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Galacticidae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Galacticidae</taxonomicName>
, must be included in the taxonomic diagnosis of the family. The similar transparent patch in 
<taxonomicName id="CFCB27195E11670EA677B23945A03EB2" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1796" class="Insecta" family="Yponomeutidae" genus="Yponomeuta" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Yponomeuta" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="150B247C9467D8C2C1BAC065BA5427FC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">Yponomeuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an array of ridges, which may be used to produce sounds (
<bibRefCitation id="C0E0B31E12E261F23DEF30FE8E50E70A" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2017.1324063" author="Agassiz, DJL" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" refId="B1" refString="Agassiz, DJL, 2017. Do small ermine moths sing? Possible stridulatory sound production in Yponomeutidae (Lepidoptera). Journal of Natural History 51: 21-22, 1229-1236. https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2017.1324063" title="Do small ermine moths sing? Possible stridulatory sound production in Yponomeutidae (Lepidoptera). Journal of Natural History 51: 21 - 22, 1229 - 1236." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2017.1324063" year="2017">Agassiz 2017</bibRefCitation>
). These ridges do not occur in the transparent patches of 
<taxonomicName id="AD48739BA4D6BCD7DB742ED929151836" authorityName="Minet" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Galacticidae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Galacticidae</taxonomicName>
. The function of such patches and their occurrence in Microlepidoptera were recently investigated by 
<normalizedToken id="2B4A3C5324BCA720C2971F82C4F73B24" originalValue="O’Reilly">O'Reilly</normalizedToken>
(2021), who coined the term aeroelastic tymbals for those hyaline spots. They produce ultrasound by wingbeat movements and are thus acoustically active structures serving as an anti-bat defence.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E6083600026916B130FDFF13366250A0" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">
